SIMPLE: supplant
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Supplant
<hw>Sup*plant"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Supplanted</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Supplanting</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[F.
<ets>supplanter</ets>, L. <ets>supplantare</ets> to trip up one's heels,
to throw down; <ets>sub</ets> under + <ets>planta</ets> the sole of the
foot, also, a sucker, slip, sprout. Cf. <er>Plant</er>,
<pos>n.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To trip up.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Supplanted</xex>, down he fell.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Milton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To displace and take the place of; to supersede; to
remove or displace by stratagem; <as>as, a rival <ex>supplants</ex>
another in the favor of a mistress or a prince</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Suspecting that the courtier had <qex>supplanted</qex> the
friend.</q> <rj><qau>Bp. Fell.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To overthrow, undermine, or force away, in order to
get a substitute in place of.</def> <mark>[obsolescent]</mark> ⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>You never will <qex>supplant</qex> the received ideas of God.</q>
<rj><qau>Landor.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To remove (a thing) and replace it with something
else.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To remove; displace; overpower; undermine;
overthrow; supersede.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 1449 --></p>

<p><ent>Supplantation</ent>⟦br⟧
